28
00:18:40.524 --> 00:18:52.304
Incoming livestream: And it is not a simple problem, it is not an easy one, but it is the one that we have to solve, because as humanity goes beyond Earth, we just simply need to not be dealing with cross-site scripting bugs.

29
00:18:54.594 --> 00:19:03.513
Incoming livestream: And, we have a little ambition at Google to get rid of memory safety bugs as well, and that is what we're gonna talk a little bit about today.

30
00:19:04.144 --> 00:19:09.894
Incoming livestream: On top of finding every bug, we have to be able to give developers the tools to not make them anymore.

31
00:19:10.524 --> 00:19:14.814
Incoming livestream: And, the technology we're gonna talk about here today

32
00:19:15.094 --> 00:19:17.303
Incoming livestream: Also lends itself to that.

33
00:19:17.944 --> 00:19:18.983
Incoming livestream: Next slide.

34
00:19:20.464 --> 00:19:26.494
Incoming livestream: So, I'm pretty sure everybody who's played with an LLM has pointed it at some code and said, please find me a bug.

35
00:19:26.794 --> 00:19:33.804
Incoming livestream: And it's actually pretty good. Even the older models are pretty good, and as we have the new generations coming out successfully.

36
00:19:33.924 --> 00:19:43.083
Incoming livestream: Kind of every, kind of, 3 to 4 months, we're seeing a massive improvement in what the large language models can do about reasoning about code.

37
00:19:43.824 --> 00:19:54.933
Incoming livestream: We wanted to go one step further, and not just look at the shallow bugs that are easy to find, but to really look at the kinds of bugs that top elite researchers

38
00:19:55.154 --> 00:20:10.303
Incoming livestream: confined. There was a 2017 study, a RAND study, that showed, just how long an expert vulnerability researcher takes to find kind of a deeply embedded bug. I think it's somewhere on the order of a month.

39
00:20:10.764 --> 00:20:12.414
Incoming livestream: For finding the bug?

40
00:20:12.524 --> 00:20:17.223
Incoming livestream: And about 22 days, for exploitation, successfully.

41
00:20:17.624 --> 00:20:29.334
Incoming livestream: But what if you could build an agentic reasoning system that could do that in a matter of hours or minutes? You could find the deep bugs much faster, more reliably, and potentially early

42
00:20:29.454 --> 00:20:31.554
Incoming livestream: In the software development lifecycle.

43
00:20:31.764 --> 00:20:48.863
Incoming livestream: So the approach that the Big Sleep team has taken to finding bugs is not just to use the LLM for the basic things you can prompt it to do, but actually to recreate the human expertise of our Project Zero team. Project Zero is a team that's been around for over a decade.

44
00:20:48.984 --> 00:20:51.403
Incoming livestream: Their goal is to get rid of zero days.

45
00:20:51.534 --> 00:21:03.194
Incoming livestream: They haven't been successful yet, but they think they're gonna get there with this technology. So they want to recreate that, kind of deep researcher experience, with three things also in mind.

46
00:21:03.394 --> 00:21:09.214
Incoming livestream: Number one, we want uncompromising quality. We do not want to produce AI slop with the bugs we find.

47
00:21:09.744 --> 00:21:15.964
Incoming livestream: We want everything that lands in a developer's hands, especially an inexperienced developer, to just work.

48
00:21:16.244 --> 00:21:17.273
Incoming livestream: Out of the box.

49
00:21:17.714 --> 00:21:22.193
Incoming livestream: Number two, we need this to be cost-effective and efficient at scale.

50
00:21:22.444 --> 00:21:26.634
Incoming livestream: We have trillions of lines of code on the planet, billions of lines of code at Google.

51
00:21:26.744 --> 00:21:30.574
Incoming livestream: And we want to run this all the time, so it's got to be fast and efficient.

52
00:21:31.004 --> 00:21:47.243
Incoming livestream: And third, as real-time as possible, right? Right now, we're all looking at brownfield code, so stuff that's already launched in production, open source code, stuff that's already out there. We want to be able to put it in the developer's user journey, so that they're not launching new bugs in the future as well.

53
00:21:47.534 --> 00:21:50.884
Incoming livestream: And we think if we do this, if we get it right,

54
00:21:51.324 --> 00:22:01.794
Incoming livestream: we can probably be creating and maintaining code that's relatively bug-free in the next couple of years, right? This is kind of within not only our ambition, but our capabilities with the tech.

55
00:22:02.514 --> 00:22:03.623
Incoming livestream: Next slide.

56
00:22:03.904 --> 00:22:09.143
Incoming livestream: So let's talk, about big sleep, and I'm not gonna do, like.

57
00:22:09.354 --> 00:22:13.144
Incoming livestream: you know, code reading here or anything. We're gonna talk architecture a little bit.

58
00:22:13.594 --> 00:22:21.094
Incoming livestream: One of the first things we realized as we studied how the researchers work is that they become deeply expert

59
00:22:21.254 --> 00:22:30.644
Incoming livestream: in the codebase they're working in. And if you've ever met a really good vulnern researcher, they kind of tend to get, you know, deep and niche in one area or two areas.

60
00:22:30.814 --> 00:22:33.223
Incoming livestream: And the way they do this is they understand the code.

61
00:22:33.384 --> 00:22:40.483
Incoming livestream: They look at the kinds of bugs that they've had in the code before, past vulnerabilities, they do variant analysis.

62
00:22:40.584 --> 00:22:44.683
Incoming livestream: And they have a really good understanding of the code architecture.

63
00:22:44.974 --> 00:22:51.374
Incoming livestream: So we have to give that to this agentic reasoning system as well. So we harness that, and that's phase one.

64
00:22:52.464 --> 00:23:00.204
Incoming livestream: We then enter into, Phase 2, which is this agentic framework that's working constantly in a loop.

65
00:23:00.294 --> 00:23:07.063
Incoming livestream: feeding back to itself. It's building hypotheses, perhaps, based on past bugs, for example.

66
00:23:07.104 --> 00:23:21.094
Incoming livestream: Here's a part of the code that I think might be vulnerable, let me test that hypothesis. To do that, it needs tools, okay? It needs a debugger, it needs the code browser, and it needs a Python interpreter so that it can write scripts for itself.

67
00:23:21.184 --> 00:23:28.264
Incoming livestream: So what it's doing is that it's not just prompting itself, it's building code, It's building test cases.

68
00:23:28.594 --> 00:23:35.123
Incoming livestream: and… It's able to test its own hypotheses and see if there's success and failure, and it's doing that

69
00:23:35.284 --> 00:23:36.964
Incoming livestream: Constantly in a loop.

70
00:23:37.084 --> 00:23:41.704
Incoming livestream: Right? This is far beyond just prompting, you know, find the cross-site scripting bug in this code.

71
00:23:42.854 --> 00:24:00.374
Incoming livestream: And it's this hypothesis and, revision that really gives the system that feel of, like, an expert researcher, right? And if you've… if you've ever met them, they sometimes are just standing in the corner staring with their coffee going, you know, I can't get that bug, I can't get that bug. This is what the LLM

72
00:24:00.584 --> 00:24:02.363
Incoming livestream: Reasoning loop is doing.

73
00:24:02.774 --> 00:24:05.683
Incoming livestream: Once it has a successful crash.

74
00:24:05.854 --> 00:24:17.444
Incoming livestream: that it thinks, might be a valid vulnerability. We then move into the verification phase. And it's looking at feedback data that's coming out of the debugger.

75
00:24:17.544 --> 00:24:21.034
Incoming livestream: And it is actually then building an exploit.

76
00:24:21.714 --> 00:24:29.573
Incoming livestream: Okay? And this proof of vulnerability is so key to getting the false positive rate to zero, and we've managed to do that.

77
00:24:29.704 --> 00:24:34.064
Incoming livestream: So every bug that comes out of there is not only a candidate for an exploit.

78
00:24:34.424 --> 00:24:44.184
Incoming livestream: For vulnerability, but it's actually provably a vulnerability. We then write a report, and again, it's the… it's Gemini writing the report, it's not a human.

79
00:24:44.634 --> 00:24:48.684
Incoming livestream: It's got the proof of vulnerability code, so the developer can test it.

80
00:24:48.844 --> 00:25:00.584
Incoming livestream: It has a high-quality report that does a step-by-step through every function, every part of the bug, explains the bug in detail, so that if you have a non-expert developer, they're gonna understand what's going on.

81
00:25:01.134 --> 00:25:10.663
Incoming livestream: And we've managed to do this to the extent where end-to-end, fully automated, without human involvement, we're getting zero false positives. And these are deep memory safety bugs.

82
00:25:10.944 --> 00:25:13.584
Incoming livestream: Right, these are not cross-site scripting bugs, these are not…

83
00:25:13.794 --> 00:25:17.144
Incoming livestream: kind of shallow integer overflows, they're kind of deep.

84
00:25:17.444 --> 00:25:22.703
Incoming livestream: In the codebase. And we've put them all online, that's the URL down there.

85
00:25:22.914 --> 00:25:25.714
Incoming livestream: Our issue tracker, so you can go in and see them.

86
00:25:25.874 --> 00:25:34.453
Incoming livestream: And see the quality of the report, and, kind of… I think all but 5 are fixed at this point, so, as I checked this morning.

87
00:25:34.574 --> 00:25:47.833
Incoming livestream: So that's big sleep. This is just the vulnerability discovery. We've done one half of the job for the developer. Now we've got to do the part that really sucks as a developer, which is fixing the code. And for that, I'm gonna pass it to Four.

88
00:25:48.824 --> 00:25:50.394
Incoming livestream: Great, thanks, Heather.

89
00:25:50.444 --> 00:25:59.783
Incoming livestream: Alright, so let's zoom out for a minute. I want to speed up a little, because I want to make sure that we have time for questions, but I have a lot to cover. So, we said we're going to try to fix every security vulnerability on Earth, and we're not kidding.

90
00:25:59.794 --> 00:26:11.814
Incoming livestream: So what does that mean? There's a whole bunch of other pieces besides the big sleeve component, right? So finding vulnerabilities is one part, but also we have to help the developers patch those vulnerabilities. I'll talk more about that in just a second.

91
00:26:11.814 --> 00:26:22.434
Incoming livestream: But one other thing that I want to make sure we at least touch on, we're not going to talk about it in detail today, is that also brand new Greenfield code that's being generated through Vibe coding frameworks

92
00:26:22.434 --> 00:26:46.164
Incoming livestream: actually needs to be secure out of the box as well, and so that's something else we're working on. We don't have time to talk about that today, but we think it's a completed thought, right? Where if you have legacy code, that we can find vulnerabilities in it, and we can get those automatically patched, that's the middle to the top arrow. If we have legacy code, we can actually proactively harden that code, I'll talk about that in a minute. And then finally, brand new code should be secure

93
00:26:46.164 --> 00:26:59.594
Incoming livestream: as much as possible out of the box, not just free of vulnerabilities, but actually using secure frameworks so those vulnerabilities aren't possible in the first place. So, we're working on all of this, but let me dive in a little bit more into the CodeMender component specifically.

94
00:26:59.594 --> 00:27:15.493
Incoming livestream: Right, so this is basically how CodeMender works. It's a project we started last year in recognition that this AI vulnerpocalypse, which, by the way, is a word that you should take away from this conference, the Vonpocalypse is coming, and so we think we should actually help arm the community with tools to solve this problem.

95
00:27:15.494 --> 00:27:25.693
Incoming livestream: So, it's not enough to find vulnerabilities, we should also help the developers patch code. Now, what are the three components of patching code? You want to make sure, one, that the patch…

96
00:27:25.944 --> 00:27:29.073
Incoming livestream: Fixes the security vulnerability, right? Two.

97
00:27:29.114 --> 00:27:47.384
Incoming livestream: that it doesn't break the code in some way that changes the functionality, right? And then three, as much as possible, you actually want to honor the idioms of the developer that had built that code previously, so that it's not just a patch for the vulnerability, but it's done in the way that the developer finds easy to digest and understand.

98
00:27:47.484 --> 00:27:51.784
Incoming livestream: So all three of those things is what CodeMender is built to solve. So how does it work?

99
00:27:52.024 --> 00:28:04.154
Incoming livestream: Well, it takes in either a verified vulnerability from Big Sleep, and the idea is to make this a full end-to-end discovery and fixing engine, right? That runs completely without human intervention.

100
00:28:04.244 --> 00:28:16.574
Incoming livestream: The other piece that I'm not sure we have time to talk about today is hardening. Basically, in a nutshell, what this is, is basically proactively looking at a codebase for things like pointer exceptions, and modifying the code through a larger patch.

101
00:28:16.574 --> 00:28:29.654
Incoming livestream: to make sure that all of those buffers are protected before the vulnerability can actually occur in the first place. So you can imagine a similar process to patching actually being used to harden code and protect pointers as well, but I won't go into that in detail.

102
00:28:29.654 --> 00:28:41.563
Incoming livestream: So, the LLM agent actually has very similar access to tools and environment like Heather just discussed, right? It can do things like debugging, it can test hypotheses. What that does is it creates a number of patch candidates.

103
00:28:41.564 --> 00:29:01.534
Incoming livestream: Right? That are potential fixes, but that's not good enough, right? We need to verify that those patches… and so some of the secret sauce of what we've been building is actually in these verification stages, and we've done a huge amount of work here. So we have verifiers of all kinds, and it's actually a pluggable system. So we actually fuzz the variables before and after the patch.

104
00:29:01.534 --> 00:29:05.104
Incoming livestream: To validate that the functionality hasn't been destroyed by the patch.

105
00:29:05.194 --> 00:29:11.554
Incoming livestream: We actually do formal verification of that section of the codebase to try to prove that that code still is functionally equivalent.

106
00:29:11.554 --> 00:29:26.333
Incoming livestream: We actually also look for differential testing. We actually do a round of fuzzing of the code with a potential candidate patch to make sure that the vulnerability is still not present by injecting the malicious inputs into that section of the code base.

107
00:29:26.334 --> 00:29:33.913
Incoming livestream: And finally, we use, of course, maybe the most obvious of all options. We use the LLM itself to view the patch

108
00:29:33.914 --> 00:29:58.533
Incoming livestream: With a very carefully crafted, pre-prompt to try to determine if that patch is also accurate as well. So, that's not all that we do, but it's a good sense of the types of things that we do, and it's only once the patch is all pass the verifier, that we would actually consider that something that's a candidate to send to the community. In some cases, none of the patches actually pass validation, and the learnings from the validation failures are actually fed back into the

109
00:29:58.534 --> 00:30:07.523
Incoming livestream: context window for the LLM to learn from the mistake and try to improve to a new set of candidate patches that are then, in turn, validated and ranked for submission.

110
00:30:07.744 --> 00:30:10.414
Incoming livestream: So that's essentially how CodeMender works.

111
00:30:10.794 --> 00:30:19.164
Incoming livestream: Just a couple notes here. We've got 178 fixes now in open source that have been autonomously generated through CodeMender.

112
00:30:19.184 --> 00:30:33.033
Incoming livestream: We have a path through a couple of different libraries, open source libraries, libwebp is one example. We've done a bunch of work in Chrome as well, to actually harden pointers in the codebase through automatically generated patches to harden those pointers.

113
00:30:33.034 --> 00:30:44.414
Incoming livestream: And, of course, we're working on doing this for internal Google systems. I think probably one criticism of our approach here that I think you could levy is that we are…

114
00:30:44.414 --> 00:30:51.094
Incoming livestream: Maybe being too cautious in making sure that we have highly verified outputs for the community before we send something out.

115
00:30:51.094 --> 00:31:10.523
Incoming livestream: We've taken a position that we really firmly believe in quality, and that people trusting the system is what's gonna lead us to be able to accelerate the community's adoption of this technology. I guess we'll see how it plays out. I think other folks have a different trade-off on the dial of sort of quicker to market, but maybe tolerating, you know, more developer toil.

116
00:31:10.564 --> 00:31:27.313
Incoming livestream: You know, I think we're trying to figure out where the right line is there. I won't go into all the details here on the bottom, except for you to recognize the fact that all of this is well and good, but those of us in the hallway here in the room all know that one of the hardest problems with patching is actually

117
00:31:27.334 --> 00:31:35.913
Incoming livestream: places in the world that struggle to actually apply patches in a timely manner. And so, that's another problem. I don't know how to solve that with AI.

118
00:31:35.914 --> 00:31:47.564
Incoming livestream: If you do, come find me, and I will be very excited to talk to you. But I think this is an important part of the puzzle, is being able to get the community and the world to patch our codebases at the speed of AI.

119
00:31:47.564 --> 00:31:51.294
Incoming livestream: Okay, and with that, I guess we'll take questions.

